-- BAE, Barclays Plc, Regal Petroleum: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 2010-12-29T07:34:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-28/bae-barclays-plc-regal-petroleum-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the close on Dec. 24.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  climbed 12.85, or 0.2 percent,
to 6,008.92. The  FTSE All-Share Index  rose 0.1 percent, while
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  fell 0.2 percent.  BAE Systems Plc  (BA/ LN): Europe’s biggest arms company may
receive an order from Oman worth as much as 1.2 billion pounds
($1.9 billion), the Sunday Times reported, citing unidentified
people familiar with the situation. The stock advanced 0.4
percent to 336.3 pence.  Barclays Plc  (BARC LN): Barclays Wealth, the private
banking business of Barclays Plc, plans to invest 350 million
pounds over five years to develop technology and infrastructure,
 Tom Kalaris , who runs the unit, said in an interview with
Spanish newspaper Expansion. The shares fell 0.1 percent to
266.95 pence.  BP Plc  (BP/ LN): TNK-BP may offer some of its assets to Oil
& Natural Gas Corp. in order to gain the Indian company’s
approval to buy BP Plc’s stake in a Vietnamese project, Interfax
said, citing  German Khan , a shareholder and executive director
at the Russian oil producer, which is half owned by BP. The
shares fell 0.4 percent to 474.55 pence.       Desire Petroleum Plc  (DES LN): The explorer said it found
no hydrocarbons in its Jacinta prospect and will now drill
deeper to evaluate the Dawn prospect. The shares tumbled 3.6
percent to 60.25 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc  (HSBA LN): Europe’s biggest bank said it
is hiring about 100 employees and creating a team specializing
in lending for existing real estate in Brazil to deal with the
demand from its partnership with Brasil Brokers Participacoes
SA, according to a statement sent by e-mail by its external
press office in the South American country. The shares retreated
0.1 percent to 667.3 pence.  Regal Petroleum Plc  (RPT LN): Shareholders in Regal
Petroleum Plc may try to block the takeover by Energees
Management Ltd., the Sunday Telegraph reported, citing retail
investor Michael Staubli. The shares rose 1 percent to 26.25
pence.  Smith & Nephew Plc  (SN/ LN): Europe’s largest maker of
shoulder and knee implants got a warning letter from the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration saying the company failed to
properly test medical devices. The shares rose 1.9 percent to
686 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
